{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696404/1930112901/0172.xml":{"full_text":"Times Daily Health Hint\nHas your child had Diphtheria Toxin-Antitoxin!\nIf not, make it a business to attend to the matter\nat once.\nGANGSTER GIRL ByjackLait\nHow a Red-Haired Beauty\nOverturned a Great City\nChapter 20.\nAnnie\u2019s taxi braked up before\na shabby and colorless building,\nthe Victory Hotel, on a side\nstreet, West of Central Park in\nthe 70\u2019s. The office was on the\nsecond floor. If one took the\nstairs, the clerk couldn\u2019t see\nfrom his regular position who\ncame or went. Maybe that was\nwhy the Victory was usually\ncrowded jam-full for all manner\nof illicit trysts behind locked\ndoors in the dingy chambers.\nAnnie walked. She turned at\nthe fourth landing and unlocked\nthe door of Room 444. As she\nthrew-the switoh a single hang\ning bulb shot pale rays over a\nmedium-sized room with a bed,\nan armchair, a plain chair, a\nlame dresser, a washstand and\na clothestree. The furnishings\nwere in keeping with the ex\nterior.\nAnnie whisked off her beret\nand her released hair lighted\nthe place more than did the\nsickly drop-light. She fixed the\nringlets with a few deft expert\ntouches \u2014and she turned at the\nsound of steps. The door opened\nand Tommy, leaning on a cane,\nclosed and clicked it behind\nhim.\n\u201cTommy boy!\u201d she cried, and\nshe ran to him.\nBut he did not stretch out\nhis strong arms. He motioned\nher to sit, and he sat on the\nother chair.\nA Straight Talk\n\u201cAnnie,\u201d he began, \u201cyou and\nI must have a straight talk\u2014\u201d\n\u201cYeh\u2014sure. But \u2014who hurt\nyou? What is it?\u201d\n\u201cOh, I got that in Freeman\u2019s\nflat when we rekidnaped Alice.\nIt\u2019s nothing.\u201d\n\u201cTommy boy\u2014before you spill\nyours, let me tell you what you\ngot to know. Freeman has put\nthe finger on you you\nknow what that means?\u201d\n\u201cI\u2014l think I do\u2014l thought\nabout it myself.\u201d\n\u201cYour life ain't worth a\nnickel as long as he lives. He\u2019ll\ndiase you thirty thousan\u2019 miles\nan\u2019 croak you in a church.\nOrd\u2019narily they drop you if you\nblow away, but when they\u2019re\nvindicative, the world ain\u2019t big\nenough to save you. Didn\u2019 they\nput Eddie Diamond on the spot\nin Denver after he quit an\u2019\nwent out West to die o\u2019 T. 8.,\nTommy boy? Didn\u2019 they take\nFat Walsh in Miami, a long\nway from Broadway?\n\u201cFreeman has always killed\nfor stric\u2019ly business an\u2019 bragged\nhe had no passions. But he\u2019s\nfound a few lately. An\u2019 among\n\u2019em, strong, is revenge!\nBitter Hate\n\u201cHe hates your soul. Even if\nyou give up an\u2019 let him muscle\nyou out o\u2019 your own prope\u2019ty,\nhe\u2019ll still have you bumped off.\nSay\u2014in my home town a gang\nster by the name of Nails Mor\nton hired a horse one day an\u2019\nwent* ridin\u2019 in Lincoln Park.\nThe horse thrun him an\u2019 stepped\non his head an\u2019 they picked up\nhis body, all bunged up.\n\u201cWhat do you think one o\u2019\nthe big shots in his mob went\nan\u2019 done? He goes to the same\nliv\u2019ry stable, hires that same\nhorse, rides him out to a lonely\nspot in the park, gets down,\nSulls a gat an\u2019 shoots the norse\ni the forehead!\n\u201cThat\u2019s gang law.\u201d\n\u201cBut \u2014why do you tell me all\nthis?\u201d\n\"Because I love you, you damn\nhandsome fool!\u201d\nShe ran to him and knelt at\nhis feet and turned up hffi fas\ncinating face.\n\u201cKiss me, boy,\u201d she breathed.\nAnd the hot blood of youth and\nmanhood burnt out all other\nconsiderations doubts, tears,\neven self-preservation\u2014when he\nanswered the call of her crim\nson lips with his own.\n\u201cFreeman Must Die\u201d\n\u201cTommy. lover,\u201d gasped\nAnne. \u201cYou don\u2019t know how I\nlove you. But you will. I must\nshow you. I must prove it to\nyou... as long as Silk Freeman\nlives your dekth sentence hangs\nover- you. So there\u2019s only one\nway out\u2014Freeman is got to\ndie!\u201d\nTommy looked down at her\nin amazement. How hotly this\nstrange girl could talk of love\nand how coldly she could talk\nof death.\nHe wondered at himself, too\n\u2014for a fortnight back of him\nhe would have shuddered at the\nidea of assassinating a human\nbeing. He had seen and heard\nmuch since th\u00b0n He didn\u2019t\nshudder now. He was about\nto let he r continue\u2014but a few\nflashes passed through his\nbrain. He held up his hand.\n\u201cAnne,\u201d he said, \u201cI\u2019m crazy\nabout you. That I know. You\nsay you are about me. I want\nto believe you.\u201d\nYou WANT to believe me?\nMy God! Lemme finish\u2014\u201d\n\u201cNnt just yet. Freeman is\nas rich as he is rotten. He\ncan pay high. What assur\nance have I that all this you\u2019re\ntelling me isn\u2019t an elaborate\nplan to win my confidence,\nstifle any possible suspicion,\nand put ME on the spot?\"\nAnnie laughed. And tears\nran down her cheeks.\n\u201cYou ain\u2019t wrong\u2014much.\nTommy boy at this minnit\u2014\nI\u2019ll tell you that part of it\u2014\nSilk is waitin\u2019 a call from me\nthat I\u2019ve GOT you on a spot\u2014\nan\u2019 two killers is waitin\u2019 ready\nto come up an\u2019 settle you\nwhere I say.\u201d\nYoung Gillespie jumped up.\n\u201cWhat!\u201d\nNot the Half of It\n\u201cSit down, Tommy boy\u2014an\u2019\nrest the sore gam. You ain\u2019t\nheard the half of it. I got\nnothin\u2019 against Freeman. He\u2019s\nbeen on the up-an-up with me.\nI wouldn\u2019 double-cross him for\ndough or for nothin\u2019 on earth\nexcept one\u2014an\u2019 that\u2019s you.\u201d\n\u201cYou admit you\u2019re a double\ncrosser\u2014and you want me to\ntrust you\u2014with my life the\nprice of it?\u201d\n\u201cExac\u2019ly. Your life is the\nprice of that trust. If you\ndon\u2019 trust me, you\u2019ll pay with\nit. If you do, I\u2019ll buy it for\nyou\u2014with Freeman\u2019s life.\u201d\n\u201cJ-just what is your\u2014h\u2019m\u2014\nplan?\u201d\n\u201cI\u2019m gonna kill Silk Free\nman!\"\n\u201cYou? Yourself? Why. you\n\u2014surely\n\u201cNever mind, lover. I never\ntold you before, but it won\u2019 be\nno virgin job for me. I\u2019m\nall p\u2019pared.\u201d\n\u201cBut why yourself? I\ncan\u2019t\n\u201cWho else can I get to do it?\nI can\u2019t go to Freeman\u2019s men.\nThey\u2019d cut my throat before I\ngot out o\u2019 the room. I can\u2019t let\nyou\u2014because they\u2019d find out\nan\u2019 run you down an\u2019 bang you\noff.\nAU Set\n\u201cI\u2019ve laid up nights figgerin\u2019\nthis all out. I got it set like\nclockwork. Remember when I\nsaid I\u2019d kill for you? I had it\nall in my noodle then.\n\u201cI\u2019m gonna croak him for my\nTommy boy in the mornin\u2019\none more night with you\u2014the\nlast!\u201d\nTommy was bewildered and\ndizzy.\n\u201cWhy the last? If you love\nme\n\u201cThe last! I can\u2019t do this\nwit\u2019out leavin\u2019 a trail like a\ntruck t\u2019rough a sand pile. If\nthey ketch me they\u2019ll take me\nfor a ride an\u2019 kill me an\u2019 weight\nmy carcass with lead an\u2019 sink\nme in a river. But they won\u2019t.\nI got my getaway all framed\npretty, too. I can disappear. I\nain\u2019 got no identity anyway\nYou have. Tall Tom Gillespie\u2019s\nkid can\u2019t disappear. Polack An\nnie\u2014yeh, that\u2019s my monicker,\nlover\u2014can take on a new name\nan\u2019 a new racket an\u2019 a new\ncountry, too\u2014an\u2019 what\u2019ll hurt\nworse\u2019n all the rest\u2019ll be\u2014she\ncan take on new hair!\u201d\n\u201cOh\u2014you wouldn\u2019t!\u201d\n\u201cYep. Got to. I\u2019ll be the mos\u2019\nfamous red-head aroun\u2019 the\nglobe an hour after they pick up\nSilk Freeman\u2019s body. But I\u2019ll be\na brunette by then. So look at\nthe old flamin\u2019 top good\u2014it\u2019s\ngivin\u2019 its last show\u2014to an au\ndience o\u2019 one.\u201d\nTommy stared at her. He was\nonly a boy. His brief underworld\ncontacts had not really hardened\nhim or changed his nature. He\nadored this thrilling, astonishing\nand electrifying woman who had\nthe dimpled body of a child, the\nirresistible beauty of a siren, the\ncourage and brutality of a\ngangster\u2014this girl who could be\ntray and murder and sacrifice\nand love\u2014this blend of passion\nand romance and treachery and\nmanslaughter.\nNo More Doubt\nHe could no longer seriously\ndoubt her. She had come clean\nto him\u2014had confessed that\nthere was murder in her heart,\nhad admitted she had done\nmurder before, had frankly\ngranted that she had taken an\nassignment from Freeman to\nwin him and lead him into the\npath of the garlic-soaked bul\nlets which this time would\npierce him in spots more vital\nthan his calf.\nAnd she was holding out her\narms to him\u2014whose shapely\nwhite arms born to embrace a\nmother and a lover rather than\nto support the deadly weight of\ngun-metal and lead.\n\u201cTommy boy,\u201d she whispered,\n\u201cyou\u2019re hot the first man I ever\nloved. I did love one\u2014my Edge\nwater Kid. They chopped him\ndown with typewriters because I\nloved him. Many a tough guy\nwent down never to stand up\naga\u2019n over that. But even the\nWHAT DOYOU\nKNOW?\nAntwort To Today\u2019 t Ttit\n(Questions on Editorial Page)\n1. Mt. Vernon. 2. Alfred Ten\nnyson. 3. St. Laurence. 4.\nlamp. 5. Pisa Italy. 6. traffic.\n7 competition. 8. artless. 9.\ntruism. 10 party 11. eight.\n12 William Wordsworth. 13.\nOcviber 19, 1781. 14. New York.\n15. eye.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nFtaltai [PWB\nFay King Considers Employed Problem Parallels Unemployment\n(l*H goihg to but Twat r\u201c there are. ItuEVE let/ FIRE SOME WReJ/\nROMANY\nJ UMAT )T WAS bdOHDERFUU 7/..S EUER-YONE J (o\u2019 \u201ci\nIwNEH WlUlrtGwk J BARGAINS NOW, JI J GO,\n\u2019L'duriNg\u2019-the) M I ee CERTAIN V* KttV n\n\u25a0fcw.iZr AmMhF\nfl I\nBy FAY KING\nThe probleth of the unemployed i\u00ab receiving attention every\nwhere. We are very glad of this, of course.\nBut there is also the problem of the employed to be considered.\nKid wasn\u2019 to me what you are\nto me.\nHe cared for me\u2014sure. Jut\nhe was a gangster, after all,\nan\u2019 I was his kind. He gimme\nhis life\u2014an\u2019 he done it with\nhis eyes wide open\u2014an\u2019 that\nwas all he had to give. Bus\nyou\u2014you\u2019re young, you\u2019re rich,\nyou\u2019re ejucated\u2014an\u2019 you\u2019re en\ngaged to a s\u2019ciety twist\u2014\u201d\nCORRECT\nMANNERS\n-Mrs. Cornelius Beeckman-\nThe Married Woman\u2019s\nCorrect Signature\nDEAR MRS. BEECKMAN:\nWill you kindly tell me how\nto sign my name after I am.\nmarried? Also which form to\nuse for business and the form\nfor social life?\nMy name is Margaret Alice\nCampbell and my fiance\u2019s name\nis Clarence Edgar Darrell.\nREADER.\nYour formal name would be\nthen Mrs. Clarence Edgar Dar\nrell and your informal name\nMargaret Campbell Darrell.\nNow then\u2014when you sign\nbusiness letters or letters to\npeople who need to be informed\nof your formal name, you must,\nlogically, sign your informal\nname first since your letters\nare written in the first person),\nand then you must give the\ninformation as to your formal\nname. Therefore, this is the\ncorrect signature:\nYours very truly,\nMargaret Campbell Darrell\n(Mrs. Clarence Darrell)\nLook at this form very care\nfully, for it is the only correct\none (except the one omitting\nthe last name of the maiden\nname, if you wish, and since it\nis a revealing breach of good\nform to sign your name in any\nother way.\nNaturally to your friends,\nyour close friends, you would\nsign only your first name. To\nthose whom you know less well,\nbut who \u2019'ould naturally know\nyour formal name, you would\nsign, either Margaret Campbell\nDarrell or Margaret Darrell (as\nI said above, this is a question\nof choice).\nYour checks would also be\nsigned like this \u2014either Mar\ngaret Campbell Darrell or Mar\ngaret Darrell. Usually the for\nmer is chosen, since this form\nregisters the important elements\nof the name\u2014the first and last\nnames of the maiden name,\nand the last name of the mar\nried name.\nTHE BEAUTY BOX\nSome of the dear gals don\u2019t\neat their oatmeal they cook it\nand put it on their faces io\nclear away blackheads If there\nare freckles as well, lemon juice\nor peroxide is added to the ce\nreal. The pack is applied fairly\nwarm. It is a bit messy, but\nwhat matters that, in the great\nand glorious cause of pulchri\ntude? Apply over the washbowl;\nlet the flakes fall where they\nmay. Retain on the skin for fif\nteen minutes, lave away with\ntepid water, rinse with cold,\nsponge the face with witch\nhazel.\nWhite spots on finger nails\nare nothings. Time removes\nthem. They are caused by\npressure on the matrix (that\nsoft little nest at the base of\nthe nail, from which the shell\nlike cells emerge. That\u2019s why\nmetal nail cleaners are for\nbidden.\nIntelligence and self-respect\nare beauty qualities to be culti\nvated by pretty girls and plain\nones. Good looks have become\nsuch a common commodity that\nwe\u2019ve got to the point that we\n\u201cI\u2019m not! That\u2019s all over!\u201d\n\u201cFine. I\u2019ll pay you off for\nthat, too, before sunrise. You\u2014\nThomas Gillespie, Jr., you asked\nme to marry you!\u201d\n\u201cI did. I meant it. I mean\nit now!\u201d\n\u201cI kno lover. It\u2019s impos\nsible. I knew that all along.\nBut you asked me\u2014an\u2019 you\nwasn\u2019 jus\u2019 good-timin\u2019 me\u2014\n\u2019\u25a0\"X\u2019\u2019- ROMANCE TO ORDER\nWhen her husband died, Alice\nVincent vowed that her son\nshould not grow up to be like\nhim. It was not that the father\nhad not been kind, generous\nand thoughtful of her during\ntheir married life. He had\nbeen all that, but his affairs\nwith other women, even though\nsome of them had been no\nmore than peccadilloes, had\nworried her youth away and\nfrequently enough had made\nher miserable.\nNo, her son, Fred, should\nnot be like that. He should\nnever make his own wife as\nmiserable as she had been when\nhe finally grew old enough to\nget married. So she carefully\nplanned his education and made\nhis upbringing her sole occupa\ntion.\nShe guarded him so that his\nevery waking hour was ac\ncounted for. He was fairly\ndocile and took this constant\nsurveillance in good part. She\nwatched him grow from year to\nyear, to become more and more\nwhat she had hoped him to be.\nAnd when he celebrated his\ntwenty-third birthday she\nthought, without self-praise,\nthat she had done her job well.\nThen she came to the conclu\nsion that it was about time for\nher to look out for a wife for\nher boy. She went over in her\nmind the available daughters of\nher friends and checked off one\nafter another as not good\nenough for Fred.\n\u201cBut there is Ella Davis,\u201d she\nsaid to herself, as she was\nthinking this all-absorbing affair\nover for the hundredth time.\n\u201cElla is really a thoroughly\nnice girl. She seems to be\nexactly like her mother, and\nI\u2019ve known her mother for 20\nyears.\u201d\nMrs. Vincent had no difficulty\nin setting her plans in motion.\nWhen next she took tea with\nMrs. Davis she broached what\nwas on her mind as guardedly\nas she thought diplomatic. But\nshe quickly saw that this care\nful attitude was quite unneces\nsary, for her friend fell in with\nher scheme, and, indeed, be-\nBy Helen Follett\nconsider what a woman is\nrather than how she looks when\nwe size her up. At least, looks\naren\u2019t the whole bag of tricks.\nAn intelligent woman carries\nherself erect, is a devotee of the\nGoddess Hygeia, is tolerant,\nminds her own business. How\nmany beautiful dummies do all\nthat?\nFashion Fancies\nIt is smart to be simple in\nstyle for daytime wear, and the\nsmartest coats are those of fine\nmaterials and furs without too\nmuch embellishment. A coat\nof forest green cloth has a wide\ncape collar and cuffs of moire\ncaracul, and is most simply\nmade without intricate treat\nment and involved silhouette.\nTake time off in the form of\na novel handbag. A lovely bag\nof black antelope has a mount\ning of fine marcasite in the\ncenter of which is a tiny\nwatch. This mounting can be\ndetached and worn as a brace\nlet.\nTAe National Daily\nMany of the employed would be only too glad to spend and\nhelp along the return of prosperity, but they have no assurance\nas to how long they may continue to be employed.\nTherefore, if they have a little money saved, they do not feel\nme, Polack Annie. From that\nmoment, boy, you owned me.\nYou touched a spot that never\nwas touched before \u2014a spot I\ndidn\u2019t even know I had. You\nput yourself on THAT spot.\nThank the saints it was me\nFreeman picked to put you cn\nanother kind.\n\u201cBoy. I\u2019ll clip Freeman with\ncame en' usiastic about it.\nFred was a good match, and\nshe knew it.\nIt was not long before the in\ngenuities of the two older wo\nmen brought Fred and Ella to\ngether frequently, and, unlike\nthe stories in books, the two\nyoung people took a fancy to\neach other. With time the fancy\nbearnce consideably stronger,\nand before six months had\npassed Fred announced to his\nmother that he had become en\ngaged.\n\u201cAnd to whom, Freddie?\u201d\nasked his mother when he told\nher the news. \u201cI hopes she\u2019s a\nreally nice girl,\" she added,\nwithout so much as a quiver of\nthe eyelids.\u201d\n\"Oh? she\u2019s a sweet girl,\nmother, he replied, \u201cand you al\nready knew her very well. It\u2019s\nElla Davis.\u201d\n\u201cI\u2019m glad, Freddie, and I hope\nyou\u2019ll both be very happy,\u201d she\nsaid as he came over to her and\nshe kissed him. \u201cAnd when do\nyou plan to be married.\u201d\n\u201cWell, mother, we thought\nwe\u2019d really like to get married\nOPINIONS ARE divided about\nthe effect of diet on the skin.\nOne eminent dermatologist\nthinks that overeating and con\nstipation are the two most\nfrequent causes of all skin\ntroubles.\nA recent article of mine de\nscribing the experience of a\nprominent Chicago physician\nin curing many stubborn skin\ndiseases by draining the gall\nbladder (medically, not sur\ngically) is an indication of the\nsame line of thought.\nDermatologists, however, are\nnoted for theories. A general\npractitioner opposed to the ex\ncessive use of cathartics wrote\nrecently that he had reviewed\na book on diseases of the skin\nand found only one disease\nin which it was not. recom\nmended to give a purge as a\npreliminary to treatment. That\nwas freckles. He said he was\nglad of that, because he had\nfreckles\nOne group of skin eruptions\ncertainly has a definite rela\ntion to foods. These are the\nhypersensitive or allergic dis\neases. Hives or urticaria is a\nrepresentative example. Cer\ntain special articles of diet,\nsuch as milk, nuts, or special\nmeats, bring on skin eruptions\nin the group of sensitized peo\nple.\nNo certain or special form\nof diet can be recommended as\nparticularly healthy for the\nskin.\nQUESTIONS FROM READERS\nA. T., Boston: \u201cWhat will\nprevent baldness?\u201d\nAnsewr: Oh! my poor, dear\nEditor\u2019s Note\u2014Four pam\nphlets by Dr. Clendening can\nnow be obtained by sending\n10 cents in coin, for each,\nand a self-addressed, stamped\nenvelope to Dr. Logan Clen\ndening, in care of Central\nPress Association, 1435 East\nTwelfth St., Cleveland, O. The\npamphlets are \u201cInfant Feed\ning,\u201d \u201cReducing and Gain\ning,\u201d \u201cInstructions on the\nTreatment of Diabetes,\u201d and\n\u201cHygiene of Women.\u201d\n\nDIET AND HEALTH\nBy Dr. Logan Clendenin,\nSATURDAY\u2014NOVEMBER 29\u20141930\na smile on my pan like I did\nKinky King when I thought he\nbanged off my Kid an\u2019 like I\ndid Goldie Gorio with his own\ngold-plated gats when I knew\nhe did. I write my own laws,\ntoo, an\u2019 I\u2019m my own jury an\u2019\nexecutioner. But you\u2019ll live.\nHah\u2014you\u2019ll be the finish o\u2019\nSilk Freeman\u2014an\u2019 that\u2019s more\u2019n\nall the coppers an\u2019 enemies an\u2019\nas soon as it could be managed.\nI\u2019m earning enough, you know,\nand Ella has a little money that\nher father left her.\u201d\nThe marriage took place three\nmonths later. The young cou\nple, after their honeymoon,\nseemed to be as happy as any\ntwo people could well be. To\nbe sure. Fred\u2019s mother thought\nthat Ella almost made a parade\nof her happiness, for Fred\nwaited on her though she were\na princess. Mrs. Vincent even\nimagined that Ella acted as\nthough she believed this to be\nher due. The girl, indeed,\nseemed to be just a trifle too\nsure of Fred and of the unde\nviating course of the years to\ncome.\nTwo of these years came and\nwent. Everything seemed to be\ngoing on as Ella had been so\nsure they would. But, some\nhow, Mrs. Vincent was not so\nsure. Certain apparently trif\nling incidents in the affairs of\nher son\u2019s life at home, while of\nno special significance in them\nselves, disturbed her.\nOne evening, as she was leav\ning a shop on Thirtyfourth\nfellow, if I knew. I would not\nbe writing articles for a paper,\nfreezing in a garret at a mis\nerable stipend. I would be\nlolling in luxury even in these\nhard times. Every day I would\nbe carried down Beacon Street\non the shoulders of an huzzah\ning crowd attended by the\nmassed marine bands and wear\ning chaplets and garlands of\norchids. The only person of\nmy acquaintance who knows\npositively the answer to this\nquestion is my barber, Leo.\nHe has a secret hemedy.\nThere are, of course, several\nkinds of baldness. One ac\ncompanied by excessive dand\nruff of the Seborrhoic variety\nis capable of being prevented.\nBut what you mean, I take\nit, is common or garden bald\nness. What the dermatologists,\nwith brutal frankness, call\nsenile baldness. The only treat\nment for this, I fear, is phil\nosophy. Renounce the thought\nof nourishing the roots of the\nhair by rubbing ungents into\nit. Renounce all ideas of\neasy conquest in amour. Take\nup a hobby\u2014the Bacon-Shakes\npeare controversy, or postage\nstamps. Collect proverbs such\nas \u201cNo grass grows on a busy\nstreet.\u201d But by all means get\nyour mind off your hair. That\nway madness and reckless ex\npenditures lie.\nHousehold Hints\nLace and net curtains often\ncontain a good deal of lime as\ndressing, and for that reason\nthey will not take a lather when\nthey are first washed. If, how\never, they are soaked in salt\nwater overnight and rinsed in\nseveral lots of clear water next\nday, they will wash quite easily.\nAfter several washings, col\nored silks are inclined to lose\ntheir gloss. When this happens,\nadd a little methylated spirit to\nthe rinsing water.\nThis Day in History\nMarcus Whitman, pioneer and leader in the col\nonization of Oregon, was massacred by the Indians\nat Waulatpu, Ore., November 29, 1847.\nthat they should risk spending it and be without funds if they\nshould find themselves suddenly among the unemployed. Wherever\npossible employers should make workers feel secure.\nMany in jobs are taking salary cuts. Will this be forgotten,\nand a return to normal pay be given reluctantly\u2014or as a raise?\ncrooked rats in his own mob\ncan ever say\u2014an\u2019 any one of\n\u2019em would o\u2019 did it a million\ntimes if they\u2019d had the guts.\n\u201cHe\u2019s got \u2019em hypped, I tell\nyou. They think he\u2019s more\u2019n\nhuman. If he was in China,\nthey\u2019d jump at their own shad\nows. But we\u2019ll see if he\u2019s hu\nman or not. We\u2019ll see if he\u2019ll\nStreet, about dusk, she saw to\nher surprise her daughter-in-law\nwalking with an attractive man\nwho was more than attentive to\nher. She pushed forward\nthrough the crowd and was sud\ndenly amazed to hear the young\nwoman saying:\n\u201cYes, tonight\u2014Fred will never\nknow\u2014his mother has brought\nhim up to be a model husband.\u201d\nMrs. Vincent heard Ella\u2019s gay\nlaugh as her escort halted a\ntaxi. Stunned and miserable,\nshe made her way to Fred\u2019s flat.\nFred was there \u2014alone. His\nmother was palpably excited,\nand yet she hesitated to plant\nsuspicions in her son\u2019s mind.\n\u201cTime for Ella to be back,\nisn\u2019t it?\u201d she said after a mo\nment.\n\u201cOh, you can\u2019t count on\nElla,\u201d said Fred. \"She\u2019s apt to\ncome in any time. She has her\nown ideas about living her own\nlife and all that sort of thing.\u201d\nEvidently he suspected noth\ning. Her careful training, it\nsemed, had been all too careful.\nA great depression assailed her\nbut nevertheless she determined\nto do nothing.\n\u201cI\u2019ve learned my lesson,\u201d she\nthought. \u201cIt\u2019s useless trying to\nrun other people\u2019s lives. From\nnow on I\u2019ll leave Fred alone, to\nwork out his own problem by\nhimself.\u201d\nShe said good night to her\nson and went home to ponder\non her years of wasted en\ndeavor. If Fred had been left\nto his own desires he would have\nbeen wiser to the ways of the\nworld\u2014probably he would never\nhave married Ella.\nAlice Vincent had muddled\nthe present and the future\nalone.\n(All names of character In this story\nare fictitious).\nYour Ruling Star\n\u2014By WILLIAM SHWADER\u2014\nTHE YEAR AHEAD\nFor Those Whose Birthday Is\nNovember 30\nIf November 30 is your birth\nday the coming year should be\none of accomplishment and\nprogress. Make use of oppor\ntunities and establish yourselef\npermanently now. Refrain from\nextravagance, save your money\nand be prepared for a more re\nstricted period which may come\nlater.\nImportant Dates: Avoid ex\ncesses of all kinds, take no\nrisks and maintain routine\nfrom December 29 to January\n4, March 29 to April 3, May 27\nto 29, June 20 to 24, June 30 to\nJuly 5, August 29 to 31, Sep\ntember 12 to October 31, also\nNovember and December. Good\nfor general affairs, make ef\nforts to advance your interests\nfrom January 10 to 13, March\n9 to 12, March 27 to 29, April\n17 to 24, April 30 to May 2,\nJuly 29 to 31, August 8 to 23.\nContradictory dates show two\nopposing influences.\nA CHILD born November 30\nwill be independent, enthu\nsiastic and talkative, with a\nlove for sports and traveling.\nHe should be successful as a\npublic speaker, reformer, edu\ncator or in some pioneeerlng\nwork.\nDecember 1\nIf December 1 is your birthday\nduring the coming year a few\ndifficulties could arise through\nextravagence or through legal\ntroubles. The spring should be\nbleed. Maybe he\u2019ll bleed ice\nwater\u2014but he\u2019ll bleed\u2014in the\nmomin\u2019\u2014lover, turn out that\nlight!\u201d\n(Copyright, 1930, King Features\nSyndicate. Inc.)\n(Does Polack Annie carry\nout her threat to kill Free\nman? Read Monday\u2019s thrilling\ninstalment.)\nADVICE TO\nLOVELORN\n\u2014By Beatrice Fairfax\nDEAR MISS FAIRFAX:\nI am a happily married wo\nman and have two lovely chil\ndren: we did not ask for any\nthing better till these terribly\nhard times came along. My hus\nband, who had a good job, is now\noften laid off for days at a time\nand doesn\u2019t make enough to pay\nour expenses.\nI could go back to the depart\nment store where I was em\nployed before I was married, but\nit\u2019s a question of the children.\nI could leave them with my\nmother-in-law, but she is rather\nqueer, has no modern ideas of\nrearing children, believes in\nwhipping and punishing un\nmercifully, and the children are\ndeadly afraid of her. When\nthere is any talk of leaving\nthem with Grandma, they take\non something awful. I\u2019m tired\nof worrying and want your ad\nvice as an outside party.\nMARY F.\nYour letter is postmarked\nfrom a large city, one that has\nseveral good days nurseries.\nWhy not investigate these, and\nconsider the one that more\nnearly meets your requirements.\nYou\u2019re quite right not to leave\nthe children with anyone of\nwhom they are afraid. We are\njust beginning to learn what a\nhandicap fear instilled in\nchildhood is all through later\nlife. But, my dear girl, if any\nmiracles of economy, or any\nwork you\u2019re able to take in at\nhome, would keep the children\nwith you. I\u2019d try to bring about\nthat happy solution. Even the\nbest of institutions fail to do\nfor children what a good, intelli\ngent mother can accomplish.\na period of activity. Don\u2019t as\nsume unnecessary obligations,\ninvestigate any business deals\nor changes particularly during\nthe closing months of 1931. Im\nportant dates: Avoid excesses of\nall kinds, take no risks and\nmaintain routine from Decem\nber 30 to January 4, March 30\nto April 4, May 28 to 30, Oc\ntober 12 to 31, November 1 to\n30, December 1 to 30. Good for\ngeneral affairs, make efforts to\nadvance your interests from\nJanuary 12 to 24, March 10 to\n12, April 19 to 26, July 10 to 13,\nAugust 13 to 27, November 10\nto 13. Contradictory dates show\ntwo opposing influences.\nA CHILD born December 1\nwill be active, restless and apt\nto be excitable. He should learn\nto control his feelings and not\nallow himself to be too easily\ninfluenced by the opinions of\nothers. He should be attracted\nto electricity, air, craft, wire\nless, philosophy or astrology.\nTimely Topics~|\nA conquering navy is seen in\nthe use by several dress de\nsigners of navy blue for both\nday and evening models. Patou\nmakes an evening frock of navy\nblue satin of a lustrous heavy\nquality and adds to it a large\nappliqued bow of purple satin.\nThe fullness of the skirt is in\njected at a very low line, and\nthe decollete is V-shaped and\nvery deep.","height":"30255","width":"24255"}}
